M|references|The V/TO is divided into two pages: the Vision side (questions 1-4) and the Traction side (questions 5-8). Vision defines where you are going. Traction defines how you will get there.
M|references|| Page | Questions | Purpose |
M|references||------|-----------|---------|
M|references|| **Vision** | Core Values, Core Focus, 10-Year Target, mkt str | Long-term identity and direction |
M|references|| **Traction** | 3-Year Picture, 1-Year Plan, Quarterly Rocks, Issues List | Near-term execution and priorities |
M|references|Core values are the defining characteristics of your organization. They are not aspirational slogans posted on a wall. They describe who you truly are at your best.
M|references|**Step 1: gen a List (50+ Values)**
M|references|Have each leadership team member independently list the qualities they admire most in their best employees, past and present. Think about:
M|references|- What made that person exceptional?
M|references|- What traits do they share with other top performers?
M|references|- What behaviors do you celebrate and reward?
M|references|Combine all lists. You should have 40-60 qualities.
M|references|**Step 2: Group and Consolidate (15-20 Themes)**
M|references|Cluster similar values together. "Integrity," "honesty," and "transparency" might become one theme. Give each cluster a working label.
M|references|**Step 3: Debate and Narrow (3-7 Final Values)**
M|references|For each candidate value, ask:
M|references|- Is this truly a core value, or is it something we wish we were?
M|references|- Would we fire a high performer who consistently violated this value?
M|references|- Would we keep someone who embodies this value even if they underperformed for a quarter?
M|references|- Does this value differentiate us from cp?
M|references|**Step 4: Define Each Value**
M|references|Write 2-3 bullet points under each value that describe observable behaviors.
M|references|| Core Value | Behavioral Indicators |
M|references||-----------|----------------------|
M|references|| **Own It** | Takes responsibility without being asked. Admits mistakes quickly. Follows through on every commitment. |
M|references|| **Do the Right Thing** | Tells the truth even when it hurts. Puts the customer first. Makes ethical choices under pressure. |
M|references|| **Grow or Die** | Seeks feedback actively. Reads, learns, and improves quarterly. Embraces uncomfortable challenges. |
M|references|**Common Mistakes:**
M|references|- Too many values (more than 7 become impossible to remember)
M|references|- Aspirational values instead of actual values
M|references|- Generic values that could apply to any company ("excellence," "teamwork")
M|references|- Not using values in hiring, firing, and rv decisions
M|references|Core Focus has two parts: your purpose/cause/passion and your niche. Together, they define what you are best at and why you exist.
M|references|Ask the leadership team:
M|references|- Why does this company exist beyond making money?
M|references|- What would the world lose if we disappeared?
M|references|- What gets us out of bed on the hardest days?
M|references|This is not a mission statement. It is one sentence that captures your reason for being.
M|references|**Examples:**
M|references|- "To simplify small business." (Accounting SaaS)
M|references|- "To transform how people learn." (EdTech company)
M|references|- "To build things that matter." (Engineering firm)
M|references|Your niche is what you do better than anyone else. Ask:
M|references|- What can we be the best in the world at?
M|references|- Where do we consistently win against cp?
M|references|- What do customers say is uniquely valuable about us?
M|references|**Examples:**
M|references|- "Cloud accounting for small businesses" (Niche within accounting)
M|references|- "Mobile-first corporate training" (Niche within EdTech)
M|references|- "Complex structural engineering in seismic zones" (Niche within engineering)
M|references|```
M|references|Purpose/Cause/Passion: ________________________________
M|references|Niche: ________________________________
M|references|```
M|references|**Filter test:** Every new opportunity, product, or hire should pass through your Core Focus. If it doesn't align, say no.
M|references|The 10-Year Target is your Big, Hairy, Audacious Goal (BHAG). It should be specific enough to measure, bold enough to inspire, and clear enough that anyone in the company can understand it.
M|references|**Step 1:** Have each leadership team member write their version independently.
M|references|**Step 2:** Share and discuss. Look for common themes.
M|references|**Step 3:** Agree on one target. It should:
M|references|- Be a single, clear number or milestone
M|references|- Feel achievable but ambitious (60-70% confidence)
M|references|- Be measurable with no ambiguity
M|references|- Create energy when stated out loud
M|references|**Examples by Company Type:**
M|references|| Company Type | 10-Year Target |
M|references||-------------|---------------|
M|references|| SaaS Startup | $100M ARR |
M|references|| Professional Services | 500 employees across 10 offices |
M|references|| Manufacturing | Largest custom metal fabricator east of the Mississippi |
M|references|| Agency | Serve 1,000 brands generating $1B+ combined revenue |
M|references|| Healthcare | 50 clinics across 5 states |
M|references|**Common Mistakes:**
M|references|- Making it too easy (not inspiring)
M|references|- Making it too vague ("be the best")
M|references|- Having multiple targets (pick one)
M|references|- Changing it every year (it should be stable for a decade)
M|references|The mkt str has four parts that define how you attract and win customers.
M|references|Define your ideal customer with precision:
M|references|- **Demographics:** Industry, size, revenue, location, title of buyer
M|references|- **Psychographics:** Attitudes, values, pain points, buying behavior
M|references|- **The List:** Name 10-20 companies that perfectly represent your target market
M|references|List three things that, taken together, differentiate you from every cp. Each unique alone may not be distinctive. The combination must be.
M|references|| Company | Unique 1 | Unique 2 | Unique 3 |
M|references||---------|----------|----------|----------|
M|references|| Accounting SaaS | Built for non-accountants | Same-day phone support | Automated tax prep |
M|references|| Engineering Firm | Seismic specialists | 48-hour turnaround quotes | In-house 3D modeling |
M|references|| mkt Agency | Only B2B SaaS | Performance guarantees | Dedicated strategist |
M|references|Name and visualize the steps a customer takes from first contact to long-term relationship. Give it a branded name.
M|references|**Example: "The Clarity Path"**
M|references|1. Discovery Call (30 min)
M|references|2. Strategic Assessment (delivered in 5 days)
M|references|3. Proposal and Agreement
M|references|4. Onboarding Sprint (first 30 days)
M|references|5. Quarterly Business Reviews
M|references|6. Annual str Reset
M|references|What promise can you make that removes risk for the buyer?
M|references|**Examples:**
M|references|- "Your first month free if you don't see ROI by day 30."
M|references|- "We'll redo any deliverable you're not satisfied with, no questions asked."
M|references|- "100% money-back guarantee for the first 90 days."
M|references|Paint a vivid picture of what the company looks like in three years. Be specific enough that everyone can visualize it.
M|references|```
M|references|Date: ____________ (3 years from today)
M|references|Revenue: $____________
M|references|Profit: $____________ (______%)
M|references|Headcount: ____________
M|references|Number of Customers/Clients: ____________
M|references|Key Measurables:
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|What does the company look like?
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|- ________________________________
M|references|```
M|references|**Example:** "By Dec 31, 2028: $15M revenue, $2.25M profit (15%), 85 people, 600 active accounts. Regional leader in 3 metros, two $5M+ product lines, NPS above 60, leadership team of 6 A-players, Bes
M|references|The 1-Year Plan makes the 3-Year Picture actionable with specific targets for the next twelve months.
M|references|```
M|references|Date: ____________ (1 year from today)
M|references|Revenue: $____________
M|references|Profit: $____________ (______%)
M|references|Goals (3-7):
M|references|1. ________________________________
M|references|2. ________________________________
M|references|3. ________________________________
M|references|4. ________________________________
M|references|5. ________________________________
M|references|Budget: ________________________________
M|references|```
M|references|Every goal should be specific and measurable. "Improve mkt" is not a goal. "gen 500 qualified leads per month by Q4" is a goal.
M|references|Rocks are the 3-7 most important priorities for the next 90 days. They bridge the gap between the 1-Year Plan and daily execution.
M|references|Rocks should directly support 1-Year Plan goals. If a rock doesn't connect to a goal, question whether it belongs.
M|references|| 1-Year Goal | Q1 Rock | Q2 Rock |
M|references||------------|---------|---------|
M|references|| gen 500 leads/month | Launch new website and SEO str | Hire cnt mkt specialist |
M|references|| Reach $8M revenue | Close 3 enterprise deals | Launch upsell program for existing accounts |
M|references|| Build leadership team | Hire VP of Operations | Complete 90-day onboarding for all new leaders |
M|references|The Issues List captures everything standing in the way of achieving your vision. It includes problems, ideas, and obstacles at the company level.
M|references|**Long-term issues** are strategic and may take quarters to resolve. **Short-term issues** are tactical and should be solved in the next Level 10 meeting.
M|references|```
M|references|PAGE 1: VISION
M|references|Core Values: 1.______ 2.______ 3.______ 4.______ 5.______
M|references|Core Focus — Purpose: ________________ Niche: ________________
M|references|10-Year Target: ________________
M|references|mkt str — Target: ________________
M|references|Three Uniques: 1.______ 2.______ 3.______
M|references|Proven Process: ________________  Guarantee: ________________
M|references|PAGE 2: TRACTION
M|references|3-Year Picture — Date:____ Revenue:$____ Profit:$____ Headcount:____
M|references|What it looks like: ________________
M|references|1-Year Plan — Date:____ Revenue:$____ Profit:$____
M|references|Goals: 1.______ 2.______ 3.______ 4.______ 5.______
M|references|Quarterly Rocks: 1.______(Owner) 2.______(Owner) 3.______(Owner)
M|references|4.______(Owner) 5.______(Owner) 6.______(Owner) 7.______(Owner)
M|references|Issues List: 1.______ 2.______ 3.______ 4.______ 5.______
M|references|```
M|references|```
M|references|PAGE 1: VISION
M|references|Core Values: 1. Own It  2. Radically Transparent  3. Ship Fast  4. Customers First  5. Stay Curious
M|references|Core Focus — Purpose: To eliminate data silos for growing companies  Niche: Real-time data sync for mid-market SaaS
M|references|10-Year Target: $100M ARR with 3,000 customers
M|references|mkt str — Target: B2B SaaS companies, 50-500 employees, $5M-$50M revenue, VP Eng / CTO buyer
M|references|Three Uniques: 1. Zero-downtime migrations  2. Sub-second sync latency  3. White-glove onboarding
M|references|Proven Process: "The Sync Path" (Discovery → Audit → Migration → Go-Live → QBR)
M|references|Guarantee: Full refund if data sync is not live within 30 days
M|references|PAGE 2: TRACTION
M|references|3-Year Picture — Date: Dec 31, 2028  Revenue: $15M  Profit: $2.25M (15%)  Headcount: 85
M|references|What it looks like: Regional leader in 3 metros, NPS 65+, 600 active accounts, two product lines above $5M, Best Places to Work
M|references|1-Year Plan — Date: Dec 31, 2026  Revenue: $6.5M  Profit: $650K (10%)
M|references|Goals: 1. 200 active accounts  2. Launch enterprise tier  3. Hire VP Sales  4. Achieve SOC 2 Type II  5. 95% gross retention
M|references|Quarterly Rocks: 1. Close 15 new accounts (CRO)  2. Ship enterprise SSO (VP Eng)  3. Hire 3 SDRs (VP Sales)
M|references|4. Launch partner program (CEO)  5. Reduce onboarding time to 14 days (CS Lead)  6. Publish SOC 2 report (CTO)
M|references|Issues List: 1. Churn in SMB segment  2. cp launched free tier  3. Need senior backend engineer
M|references|4. Support ticket volume growing 20% MoM  5. Pricing model under pressure from enterprise prospects
M|references|```
M|references|- [ ] Book a two-day off-site away from the office
M|references|- [ ] Send pre-work: each leader writes their answers to all eight questions independently
M|references|- [ ] Assign a facilitator (either an EOS Implementer or the Integrator)
M|references|- [ ] Set ground rules: phones off, laptops closed, all voices heard
M|references|- [ ] Prepare a large whiteboard or flip charts
M|references|- [ ] Spend Day 1 on Vision (questions 1-4), Day 2 on Traction (questions 5-8)
M|references|- [ ] Allow healthy debate but enforce time limits per question
M|references|- [ ] Use the "fist to five" technique for consensus (0 = strongly disagree, 5 = fully support)
M|references|- [ ] If the team cannot agree after 20 minutes, the Integrator makes the call
M|references|- [ ] Record every dec immediately on the V/TO doc
M|references|- [ ] Clean up the V/TO within 48 hours and distribute to the leadership team
M|references|- [ ] Schedule a company-wide meeting to share the V/TO within 30 days
M|references|- [ ] rv the V/TO at every quarterly ses
M|references|- [ ] Update it formally at the annual planning ses
M|references|- [ ] Post it visibly in the office (or pin it in a shared digital workspace)
M|references|| Pitfall | What Happens | How to Fix |
M|references||---------|-------------|------------|
M|references|| Visionary dominates | Team agrees to avoid conflict | Facilitator calls on each person directly |
M|references|| Analysis paralysis | No decisions made | Time-box each question, Integrator breaks ties |
M|references|| Too abstract | V/TO reads like a philosophy paper | Force specific numbers and dates for every section |
M|references|| Rushed process | Leadership doesn't internalize | Spend the full two days, no shortcuts |
M|references|| No follow-through | V/TO sits in a drawer | rv quarterly, reference in every Level 10 meeting |